snippet.textDisplay:
Running into someone in hugeass LA is not necessarily impossible as you imply (more than imply). In 1975 when I was living out in Hollywood (the "almost normal" part for poor folks haha) I dated a woman for a few months. Well, I didn't have a lot of experience with women yet, so it went all haywire, thanks to me. Anyway, I then began dating another woman. It was the best place ever for finding girlfriends, at least for me! So, one evening, the second girlfriend and I went to the movies.
Well, about halfway through the movie, the person sitting RIGHT IN FRONT OF ME, turned around... !! It was my first girlfriend whom I had not seen for a while. She was at that movie with her son. She said she recognized my voice!
OMG, I thought to myself, here we are in the city of 10 million or however many it is, and who would ever think this would happen? BUT as a friend of mine told me years later. LOW PROBABILITY events do happen! haha That's one way of looking at it.
Therefore, I do not agree with you. I believe you COULD run into someone in LA twice in a day.

snippet.textDisplay: Sin #3 (0:35) is not a sin at all. It is a call back to one of the marketing problems they had in the golden age of cinema. When they had a movie with two equal status stars (say, for example, Redford and Newman or Sinatra and Kelly), they had to figure out a way to bill them so neither star's name would seem more important than the other. So they would have to do something like we see in that shot. They would put one actor on the more prominent left, but but the other ones name on the left. Or they would put one name on the left, but lower than the one on the right. That shot, with Brad Pitt on the left and Dicaprio on the right, but the names switched around, is the perfect example of that. Sin to the CinemaSin guys for that one.
